==Latin==
===Pronunciation=== * {{a|Classical}} {{IPA|/Ààe.oÀê/|lang=la}} * {{audio|la-cls-eo.ogg|Audio (Classical)}}
===Etymology 1=== From {{etyl|ine-pro|la}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*h‚ÇÅey-}}. Cognate with Ancient Greek {{term|sc=polytonic|Œµ·º∂ŒºŒπ|tr=eimi|lang=grc||I go}}, Sanskrit {{term|sc=Deva|‡§è‡§§‡§ø|tr=√©ti||goes|lang=sa}}, Hittite {{term|sc=Xsux|tr=iyatta|íÑøíÑøíÄÄíã´íã´||goes|lang=hit}}, Old Persian {{term|sc=Xpeo|tr=aitiy|êé†êé°êé´êé°êéπ||goes|lang=peo}}, Old Church Slavonic {{term|sc=Cyrl|–∏—Ç–∏|tr=iti|lang=cu}}.
====Verb==== {{la-verb|eo|e≈ç|ire|ƒ´re|ii|iƒ´|itum|itum|pattern=[[irregular]]}}
# I [[go]]. #: ''Romani '''ite''' domum!'' #:: Romans, '''go''' home! #: ''Romani '''ierunt''' domum.'' #:: The Romans have gone home. # I [[proceed]], [[advance]]. # I [[result]], [[happen]] as a consequence. # I [[prepare]] (for some action); I [[set about]]. # {{context|legal|lang=la}} I [[accede]], go over to the opposing opinion or other side in voting. # {{context|business|lang=la}} I [[go for]]; I am [[sold]] at (a certain price).
=====Usage notes===== The basic meaning "[[go]]" applies to any kind of animate or inanimate motion: [[walk]], [[ride]], [[sail]], [[fly]], etc.
=====Inflection===== Irregular conjugation, but similar to [[Appendix:Latin fourth conjugation|fourth conjugation]]. The third principal part is most often contracted to {{term|ii|iƒ´|lang=la}}, but occasionally appears as {{term|ivi|ƒ´vƒ´|lang=la}}. Likewise, the perfect active infinitive and pluperfect subjunctive stem are most often contracted to {{term|isse|lang=la}}, but rarely can be found in the full form {{term|iisse|lang=la}}.
